<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="45.[146,976,276,1549]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[170,266,1392,1414]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is the only 
<taxonomicName box="[524,763,1392,1414]" class="Insecta" family="Latridiidae" genus="Akalyptoischion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[524,685,1392,1413]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Akalyptoischion</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
known from 
<collectingRegion box="[909,972,1392,1414]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Texas</collectingRegion>
. All other species occur from 
<collectingRegion box="[442,525,1419,1441]" country="United States of America" name="Arizona" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Arizona</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[576,629,1419,1441]" country="United States of America" name="Utah" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Utah</collectingRegion>
westwards. 
<emphasis box="[755,975,1419,1440]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Aklayptoischion 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartley, Andrews &amp; McHugh" authorityYear="2008" box="[922,975,1419,1440]" class="Insecta" family="Latridiidae" genus="Akalyptoischion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="texas">texas</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
may be distinguished from all other glabrous species except 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartley, Andrews &amp; McHugh" authorityYear="2008" box="[807,895,1446,1467]" class="Insecta" family="Latridiidae" genus="Akalyptoischion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas">
<emphasis box="[807,895,1446,1467]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A. gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of a Y-shaped carina on the mesosternum (
<figureCitation box="[752,829,1473,1495]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="15.[167,206,1116,1135]" captionTargetBox="[173,953,196,1094]" captionTargetId="figure-185@15.[169,953,194,1094]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs. 22–24. 22) A. atrichos, male, pterothorax, ventral view; 23) A. polytremetron, female, pterothorax, ventral view; 24) A. texas, pterothorax, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4912102" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4912102/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
). It is easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hartley, Andrews &amp; McHugh" authorityYear="2008" box="[360,450,1500,1521]" class="Insecta" family="Latridiidae" genus="Akalyptoischion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas">
<emphasis box="[360,450,1500,1521]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">A. gigas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its distribution, smaller mandibles and the impunctate median surface of abdominal ventrite I.
</paragraph>
